      <div xml:id="NA91-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi talaimakaṭku varaivu malintu uraittatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said to HER, rejoicing about the marriage.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA91">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nīyuṇarn taṉaiyē tōḻi vīyukap</l>
<l>            puṉṉai pūtta viṉṉiḻa luyarkaraip</l>
<l>            pāṭimiḻ paṉikkaṭa ṟuḻaiip peṭaiyō</l>
<l>            ṭuṭaṅkirai tērun taṭantā ṇārai</l>
<l>            yaiya ciṟukaṭ ceṅkaṭaic ciṟumīṉ </l>
<l>            mēkkuyar ciṉaiyiṉ mīmicaik kuṭampait</l>
<l>            tāyppayir piḷḷai vāyppaṭac coriyuṅ</l>
<l>            kāṉalam paṭappai yāṉā vaṇmakiḻp</l>
<l>            perunal līkainañ ciṟukuṭip poliyap</l>
<l>            puḷḷuyirk koṭpiṉ vaḷḷuyir maṇittārk </l>
<l>            kaṭumāp pūṇṭa neṭuntēr</l>
<l>            neṭunīrc cērppaṉ pakalivaṇ varavē.</l>
        </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>You have realised, friend,</l>
<l rend="indent">that the man from the coast of the long water comes here by day,</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the long chariot yoked with swift horses</l>
<l rend="indent2">with bell garlands [and] abundant breath, to the lively agitation</l>
<l rend="indent4">of the birds,</l>
<l rend="indent2">while our small hamlet glitters with great good gifts, delightful</l>
<l rend="indent2">in unending generosity in the gardens by the seashore grove,</l>
<l rend="indent3">where the broad-footed heron<note place="foot">The connection between line 1-4 is as loose as the translation conveys. If the idea is that the <term xml:lang="ta">tāy</term> is a <term xml:lang="ta">nārai</term>, the <term xml:lang="ta">peṭaiyoṭu</term> seems a little odd.</note> that searches prey together</l>
<l rend="indent3">with [its] female, stirring the chilly sea, buzzing with singing,</l>
<l rend="indent4">on the high shore with pleasing shade where the Puṉṉai</l>
<l rend="indent4">has flowered to shed [its] blossoms,</l>
<l rend="indent2">pours forth the beautiful, small-eyed, red-rimmed, little fish</l>
<l rend="indent3">into the mouth of young ones calling for [their] mother,</l>
<l rend="indent4">in the nest on the height of the high, high branch.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">mēkku uyar ... mī micai</term>: four words for being high in connection with a single branch?</note></l>
        </lg>
